title: For Sale/Trade:  Sig Sauer P229 Like New Condition 40Cal P226 Compact
location: Advance - Yadkinville - Mocksville, Winston Salem, North Carolina
postcontent:
P229 - Second mag still in wrapper -  with box and such - 3 dot combat sights (not night). Unused warranty card MSRP - New is 975.00    $575 Firm

Sig Info:
The P229 is a compact firearm often used for duty and/or concealed carry purposes. The standard version features a DA/SA trigger. The pistol has also been made available in a DAK (Double Action Kellermann) model, which is a DAO system with two trigger reset points, and a lighter, smoother pull than that of traditional DAO handguns. Most of the above-mentioned factory variants of the P226 are also available for the P229, including the Equinox option, Elite lineup, as well as a SAS GEN 2 model.

The P229 differs from its cousin the P226 in several respects, and was originally introduced to supplement and then replace the P228 by adding the .357 SIG and .40 S&W as available chamberings. The P229 was the first production handgun introduced that could chamber the .357 SIG round.[25] The P226 and P228 were originally manufactured using a stamped-steel slide on an aluminum alloy frame. The P229 consists of a CNC-milled stainless steel slide, typically colored black with a Nitron finish. The P229's milled steel slide was introduced to handle the higher slide velocities created by the .357 SIG and .40 S&W loads, which the stamped slide of the P228 could not handle without the use of a much stiffer recoil spring. This would have made manual slide-retraction much more difficult and the use of a milled stainless slide (coupled with the new milling and stainless production capabilities found in the U.S. factory) with a standard weight recoil spring made more sense.

A standard weight recoil spring for the P229 is 71 N (16 lbf). A spring weight of 89 N (20 lbf) or higher would have been required if a stamped slide was used for the .40 S&W or .357 SIG chamberings. The SAAMI maximum chamber pressures of 9mm, 9mm +P, .40 S&W, and .357 SIG are as follows: 240 MPa (35,000 psi); 265 MPa (38,500 psi); 240 MPa (35,000 psi); and 280 MPa (40,000 psi). The slide on the P226 was redesigned in a similar fashion, and civilian sales of the P228 were discontinued in early 2005 due to declining sales and the advent of the P229 in 9mm. The P226 and P229 are both available with optional accessory rails and optional forged stainless steel frames.

The P229 can be chambered in .22 LR, 9mm, .40 S&W or .357 SIG. Changing between .40 S&W and .357 SIG is as simple as switching out the barrel. Conversion barrels, from companies such as Bar-Sto Precision Machine,[26] also allow a P229 or P226 to change between a .40 S&W/.357 SIG to a 9mm caliber. Magazines shipped with .40 S&W models will also accept .357 SIG cartridges. The 9mm model (both railed and non-railed) can be converted to .22 LR, but in the past its receivers were not designed to provide the space needed for handling the larger rounds of .357 SIG and .40 S&W. As SIG Sauer has slowly begun adopting the E2-style grip system across the P229 model range in 2011—a move similar to what is also happening to the larger P226—they have also begun using the .357 SIG/.40 S&W spec frame dimensions for their factory 9mm P229s, presumably to streamline the number of variations in parts needed to be kept in inventory. Although the manufacturer has announced that older-configuration magazines will continue to operate in the new receiver configuration, SIG Sauer has nonetheless revised new P229 9mm factory magazines to a design that is specific to the resized magazine well of the newly reconfigured receiver/frame. As a consequence, the newer magazines are not back-compatible, due to their larger diameter.

title: For Sale:  Triple-matching KA-stamped W German Sig P226 CPO 9mm Hi Cap Collection
location: Clayton, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Last January, I bought a pistol I’d always wanted. Over the years I longed for it, I only found a few quite like it. I bought it with the thought that I might make this West German Sig P226 into a competition gun, and even picked up some pieces with which to do that. In the end, my SIG-loving heart just couldn’t modify this classic P226, as it deserves to be made a safe queen or fired often in its intended configuration. With my focus now on some other 3-gun tools, I thought I’d see if there was one of you who would love her and treat her like the regal lady she is. 

She is a “KA” stamped, classic SIG- Sauer P226 9 mm. This makes her West German manufactured (of course therefore much sought after by loyalists) with Exeter, NH as the import location. She has additional German proof marks. 

To me, this is where it gets cool. Most of the W German P226’s in police service were retired somewhere around the 10 year mark, and by 1993 the 226 production was occurring in the US. This means that by 2003 most of the police service weapons (read that as low, almost known, round count) were traded in for their replacements. 11 years later, they have often been shot tons more, and when you buy one used the overhaul is $140.00 (with shipping) through SIG. This does not include refinishing (100.00 for original Nitron,) any small parts, or barrel if necessary. 

When I found this pistol I was truly surprised. It was a police trade to SIG and they made it a SIG certified pre-owned. It was overhauled by Sig and graded “excellent.” The only other SIG of that age I’ve seen this clean was mine- on the day I bought it in 1993. It comes with 2 SIG 15-round magazines, and all the stuff you’d find in a new gun box today. It still has the CPO band on the handle. I’ve never loaded it, never chambered a round, never fired it. The protectant is still on the slide. The breech face is not marred. I‘ve stared at her LOTS but I just can’t bring myself to modify this one. There are no finish issues- what you see in the photos is the protectant form the Sig packaging. It is truly like walking into a store in 1990 and picking up the real West German classic.

I will cover the transfer fee if we use my LGS in Clayton. Otherwise, we can transfer at your preferred FFL in the Raleigh area at your expense. 

In addition to the two supplied 15 round magazines, this package also includes 4 Sig-Sauer and 3 Mec-Gar 20 rd magazines, 4 Mec-Gar AFC 18 rd magazines, and a package of Magwell grips (all brand new, in package, original value $380.00.) Price for the entire package is $975.00. Firearm only: $725.00. Prices are firm.

Only trade I would consider is for a Barnes Precision Machine complete upper or rifle.
